2. _If_ \(\lambda\) _is additionally neutral, then_ \(\lambda\)_-_MR _is solvable in_ \(\mathsf{k}^{\mathsf{2k}}\cdot(2^{n}+2)^{\mathsf{2k}}\cdot(n+m)^{O(1)}\) _time and_ \((\mathsf{k}+1)^{4\cdot 2^{n}}(n+m)^{O(1)}\) _time and a shortest reconfiguration path can be found in the same time. Thus, it is FPT wrt._ \(n+\mathsf{k}\) _and in XP wrt._ \(n\)_._

For CC, the following lemma shows that for a large enough committee size \(\mathsf{k}\) there is always a reconfiguration path: The score of each committee is determined by at most \(n\) relevant alternatives since each voter contributes a score of at most one. Due to this, we can find a shortest path if the symmetric difference between \(W\) and \(W^{\prime}\) is very large (Case (i)), by only exchanging the alternatives in the symmetric difference. Otherwise (Case (ii)), we can still find a path in polynomial time by also exchanging alternatives that are shared by both \(W\) and \(W^{\prime}\).

**Lemma 1**.: _For every instance of CC-MR with \(\mathsf{k}\geq 2n\) there exists a reconfiguration path between \(W\) and \(W^{\prime}\). Moreover,_

1. _If_ \(\left|W\setminus W^{\prime}\right|\geq 2n\)_, then we can find a shortest one in polynomial time._
2. _If_ \(\left|W\setminus W^{\prime}\right|<2n\)_, then we can find one with length at most_ \(\lceil\frac{2n}{\delta_{\mathrm{c}}}\rceil\) _in polynomial time._

Proof.: Let \(I=(\mathcal{P},\mathsf{k},\delta_{\mathrm{c}},\delta_{\mathrm{s}},W,W^{\prime})\) denote an instance of CC-MR. We first consider the case when \(\delta_{\mathrm{c}}=1\) and show how to adapt the proof for \(\delta_{\mathrm{c}}\geq 2\) at the end. First, observe that we can always find a size-\(n\) committee of \(W\) (resp. \(W^{\prime}\)) with score at least \(\textsc{sc}(W)\) (resp. \(\textsc{sc}(W^{\prime})\)). Hence, the idea is to find a size-\(n\) committee \(A\subseteq W\) (resp. \(B\subseteq W^{\prime}\)) such that \(\textsc{sc}(A)=\textsc{sc}(W)\) (resp. \(\textsc{sc}(B)=\textsc{sc}(W^{\prime})\)) and perform exchanges to obtain a committee that contains \(A\cup B\), and then switch out alternatives that are not contained in \(W^{\prime}\). Note that \(A\) and \(B\) can be found in polynomial time by iteratively deleting "redundant" alternatives from \(W\) and \(W^{\prime}\), respectively. To show the statement, we distinguish between two cases. Figure 2 illustrates the constructions used in the proofs.

**Case 1:**\(\left|W\setminus W^{\prime}\right|\geq 2n\) or \(\left|W\setminus(W^{\prime}\cup A)\right|\geq\left|B\setminus W\right|\). Note that the first condition implies the second condition since \(\left|A\right|=n=\left|B\right|\). To implement the exchange idea, let \(X\subseteq W\setminus(W^{\prime}\cup A)\) be an arbitrary committee of \(\left|B\setminus W\right|\) alternatives. We divide the exchanges into two parts. In the first part, we step-by-step exchange all alternatives from \(X\) with all alternatives from \(B\setminus W\). It is straightforward to verify that every committee obtained until now has score at least \(\textsc{sc}(W)\) because it always contains \(A\), and the last committee obtained has score at least \(\textsc{sc}(W^{\prime})\) since it contains \(B\). In the second part, we step-by-step exchange the remaining alternatives from \(W\setminus(W^{\prime}\cup X)\) with the remaining alternatives from \(W^{\prime}\setminus(W\cup B)\). It is straightforward to verify that every committee obtained in the second part has score at least \(\textsc{sc}(W^{\prime})\geq\textsc{sc}(W)-\delta_{\mathrm{s}}\) since it contains \(B\).The exchange sequence yields a reconfiguration path of shortest length \(\left|[W\Delta W^{\prime}]/2\right|\). If \(\delta_{\mathrm{c}}\geq 2\), then we take every \(\delta_{\mathrm{c}}\)-th element on the path, including \(W\) and \(W^{\prime}\). All these committees have score at least \(\textsc{sc}(W)-\delta_{\mathrm{s}}\) by construction and the path is of the shortest possible length \(\left|[W\Delta W^{\prime}]/(2\,\delta_{\mathrm{c}})\right|\).

**Case 2:**\(\left|W\setminus W^{\prime}\right|<2n\) and \(\left|W\setminus(W^{\prime}\cup A)\right|<\left|B\setminus W\right|\). We proceed in three parts. For the sake of brevity, let \(W_{1}=W\setminus(W^{\prime}\cup A)\) and let \(B_{1}\subseteq B\setminus W\) denote a committee of \(\left|W_{1}\right|\) alternatives arbitrarily chosen from \(B\setminus W\). First, we step-by-step exchange the alternatives in \(W_{1}\) with the alternatives in \(B_{1}\). Afterwards, we select a committee \(X\subseteq(W\cap W^{\prime})\setminus(A\cup B)\) of \(\left|B\setminus W\right|-\left|W_{1}\right|\) arbitrary alternatives, and step-by-step exchange the alternatives in \(X\) with the remaining alternatives in \((B\setminus W)\setminus B_{1}\). Note that this is possible since \(\left|(W\cap W^{\prime})\setminus(A\cup B)\right|\geq\left|W\cap W^{\prime} \right|-\left|A\right|+\left|A\setminus W^{\prime}\right|-\left|B\right|+ \left|B\setminus W\right|=\left|W\right|-\left|W\setminus W^{\prime}\right|- \left|A\right|+\left|A\setminus W^{\prime}\right|-\left|B\right|+\left|B \setminus W\right|\geq-\left|W_{1}\right|+\left|B\setminus W\right|\); the last inequality holds since

